<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-803-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 803 234.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  Sept 1990 v3 n9 p46(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>News from the font front. (What's Up!) (Adobe Systems Inc.'scomputer font and printer software, utility programs and hardwareinterpreter) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>DeJean, David.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Adobe Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ADBE.andO;Product:   Type Manager (Printer software) (product introduction)Adobe Type Set 1 (Computer font) (product enhancement)Font Foundry (Utility program) (product enhancement)PostScript (Printer software) (usage).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionUpdatingFontsPrinter SoftwareUtility ProgramsCartridge Disk.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Adobe falered in the font war lost winter as Apple and Microsoft ganged up onit.andP;  But important new customers (IBM, Xerox and Kodak among them) and ablitz of new products have put the company that invented PostScript back inthe battle (though its secret weapon, Adobe Type Manager for Windows, won'tbe ready until later this fall).andM;Adobe, in Mountain View, California, is finally selling its most basicproduct, a hardware PostScript interpreter, directly to end users.andP;  (Strangeto think that such an important product has been  available only throughthird-party printer makers until now.) it's a $495 cartridge for LaserJetSeries II versions and is calculated to fill a gap in the marketplace.andP;  Thereare 2 million LaserJet Series IIs out there, but no true PostScript cartridgefor them.andP;  Hewlett-Packard sells a true PostScript cartridge for the LaserJetIIP and ill, so Adobe doesn't need to.)andM;The cartridge will come with an autoswitch TSR that puts the printer intoeither PostScript or PCL mode.andP;  The cartridge doesn't include any fonts, buttwo PostScript font cartridges are being released, and the interpreter willship with 35 outline fonts (the standard set of faces installed in the AppleLaserWriter Plus) and Font Foundry, Adobe's font-generating utility, on disk.andM;Adobe also intends to upgrade all the Type I PostScript typefaces for the PCby adding Font Foundry, a utility that works like Bitstream's Fontware toturn outline fonts into downloadable bitmap fonts for HP printers andgenerate the matching screen fonts.andP;  The new versions of the PC Type 1 fontswith Font Foundry will take some time to arrive--there are 140 packages to beconverted, and more coming every month.andP;  Typically, the Adobe packagesinclude four weights of a type family and cost $185 (800-344-8335).andO;</TEXT></DOC>